        "0e237a06": {
          "questionId": "0e237a06",
          "textAnswers": {
            "answers": [
              {
                "value": "I believe the document gives more weight to concerns related to Kichwa than I'd expect. These communities would use their language mainly to connect among them, and not that much to report a disaster-related problem. In such cases, I'd expect them to use Spanish since this is the official language responders and authorities would understand. This would be the case for platforms such as Twitter, that are used as broadcasters. But on Facebook I can imagine finding more Kichwa/Shear groups/communities where they actually write in this language. I'd emphasize the limit more due to the lack of the Ecuadorian lexicon, local name entities and locations."
              }
            ]
          }
        },
